00:01:55.166 --> 00:01:59.166
I grew up with lots of pianos
and so different classes

00:01:59.166 --> 00:02:02.166
were being held in different
parts of the house,

00:02:02.166 --> 00:02:04.667
in the music room, dining room, living room,

00:02:04.667 --> 00:02:06.333
'cause there were
pianos all over the place.

00:02:06.333 --> 00:02:11.500
So I grew up hearing Chopin,
Polonaise, stuff like that

00:02:11.500 --> 00:02:13.133
basically.

00:02:13.133 --> 00:02:15.700
It wasn't until about fourth
grade and I realized

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:17.233
everyone didn't play piano.

00:02:17.233 --> 00:02:18.767
[laughing]

00:02:18.767 --> 00:02:22.300
Eric: Anyway, time passes,
I get better I get better.

00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:25.600
They turn me over to the
Southern Music School

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:29.333
in Philadelphia where I start
getting into, woo hoo,

00:02:29.333 --> 00:02:32.300
we started getting into Chopin,

00:02:32.300 --> 00:02:36.100
a etudes, and Beethoven and,
you know, the harder pieces,

00:02:36.100 --> 00:02:39.066
and then I get exposed to jazz,

00:02:39.066 --> 00:02:43.100
I ended up meeting Wynton
Marsalis when I was about 13.

00:02:43.100 --> 00:02:44.700
I get enamored with the jazz,

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:48.333
ethos, and the lifestyle 
and the look of it New York

00:02:48.333 --> 00:02:50.500
and wanted to be there,
be a part of it.

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:51.800
New York, New York.

00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:54.133
And so I ended up getting
a full scholarship

00:02:54.133 --> 00:02:55.867
to the Manhattan School
of Music,

00:02:55.867 --> 00:02:58.033
go there and graduate there,

00:02:58.033 --> 00:03:00.166
graduate immediately
hit the road

00:03:00.166 --> 00:03:03.033
with Cassandra Wilson
doing tours,

00:03:03.033 --> 00:03:05.600
then I ended up hitting tours with Wynton Marsalis

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:08.333
and then John Hendricks,

00:03:08.333 --> 00:03:12.500
and then I end up winning --

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:15.033
this is only a small international piano competition

00:03:15.033 --> 00:03:16.934
in 1999.

00:03:16.934 --> 00:03:19.633
Then I go on the road for
two years with Elvin Jones.

00:03:19.633 --> 00:03:22.533
That was sort of my sorcerer's
apprentice,

00:03:22.533 --> 00:03:27.266
Elvin Jones was the drummer
who supported

00:03:27.266 --> 00:03:32.333
and co-innovated a style of
music with John Coltrane,

00:03:32.333 --> 00:03:36.500
and so I got a up-close
and personal dosage

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:39.667
from a real
master of music.

00:03:39.667 --> 00:03:41.333
Went back out with
Wynton Marsalis

00:03:41.333 --> 00:03:42.700
after I finished that tenure,

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:45.400
did a little bit with
Roy Hargrove,

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:50.233
and then I got to a point where there was a certain kind

00:03:50.233 --> 00:03:54.967
of power and emotion and angst
that I was looking to express

00:03:54.967 --> 00:04:02.367
more regularly and I decided
to strike out on my own.

00:04:02.367 --> 00:04:06.033
By the way, I spent a lot of
time with the chess hustlers

00:04:06.033 --> 00:04:08.700
in Washington Square Park
and Greenwitch Village,

00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:11.367
