00:10:08.934 --> 00:10:10.533
Eric: So it's the same
kind of ethos

00:10:10.533 --> 00:10:12.734
it's just a different
rhythmic quality.

00:10:12.734 --> 00:10:16.066
But for me, as a piano player,

00:10:16.066 --> 00:10:17.800
faced with a situation
where you know,

00:10:17.800 --> 00:10:19.767
everyone's like, well,
everything's already been done.

00:10:19.767 --> 00:10:25.000
You know, there's nothing more
to do, that typical thing.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.600
This is one thing that hasn't
been really exploited

00:10:27.600 --> 00:10:30.934
where we take these kind of
intervals and run around

00:10:30.934 --> 00:10:32.900
in the left hand with
'em like a guitar player

00:10:32.900 --> 00:10:35.166
and use them as
a support system.

00:10:35.166 --> 00:10:37.900
To me that was being
foreshadowed by McCoy Tyner,

00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:40.066
Elvin Jones,
Coltrane connection.

00:10:40.066 --> 00:10:44.166
With that real extremist kind
of highly emotionalized,

00:10:44.166 --> 00:10:48.100
extra virgin, expressionist type
of behavior or, uh, playing.

00:10:48.100 --> 00:10:53.367
And so the alternative rock
for me was a perfect link.

00:10:53.367 --> 00:10:55.767
'Cause most of my skills
were geared for that

00:10:55.767 --> 00:10:59.100
that's my favorite kind of improvisational style

00:10:59.100 --> 00:11:02.200
and so when I was turned
on to the fact that,

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:03.533
yeah, there's a band called Lincoln Park.

00:11:03.533 --> 00:11:07.233
They've got tunes that are,
like, designed for you to really

00:11:07.233 --> 00:11:11.100
bash your brains out
or bash your heart out

00:11:11.100 --> 00:11:13.900
without anyone saying,
well, you shouldn't --

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:15.600
those tunes are designed.

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:17.667
You know, a guy screaming
in the microphone,

00:11:17.667 --> 00:11:18.500
you know what I mean?

00:11:18.500 --> 00:11:21.934
So for me it's like, yeah,
it's the perfect way

00:11:21.934 --> 00:11:26.266
to take all of these techniques
that most jazz piano players

00:11:26.266 --> 00:11:33.333
are using but take 'em to a zone
that no one's really going to.

00:11:33.333 --> 00:11:36.467
You know, because the thing
about is that

00:11:36.467 --> 00:11:38.934
physiologically it's difficult.

00:11:38.934 --> 00:11:41.100
You know, this is a horizontal
plane and vertical,

